#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
                                              Important Transactions
#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#

[PA10 - Personnel File]
-----------------------
This transaction provides a view of all infotypes in which the employee is registered. 
It allows a comprehensive view of the employee's personnel file, consolidating essential information in one place.

PA70 - Fast Entry
-----------------
Enables the efficient registration of multiple employees in the same infotype. 
For example, it is useful for entering information in infotypes 14 and 15, related to additional payments and attire, notifications, respectively.

PA40 - Employee Actions
-----------------------
In this transaction, specific actions related to a particular employee are created. 
This process is linked to infotype 0000, which covers general employee information.

#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
                         (Post Scriptum) - Automatic Registration of Payroll Status Infotype
#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
When an employee is hired, the Payroll Status infotype is automatically registered in the background. 
This streamlines the onboarding process by automatically recording the employee's payroll status.

#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
                                                    Constraints
#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
Constraints on infotype registrations, with the most well-known being levels 1, 2, and 3:

Level 1
-------
Constraints that limit the alteration of data over time when it becomes illogical to make changes. 
For example, modifying the country of birth while the individual is alive.

Level 2
-------
Allows changes in the record but with a time expiration, such as a change in a life insurance policy.

Level 3
-------
The record may or may not exist, and if it exists, there may be more than one instance of that record.


These constraints, categorized at different levels, offer precise control over changes in employee data over time, 
ensuring consistency and logic in information records.
